Scotland’s independent schools have many great academic achievements behind them, and it continues in 2018 with a number of outstanding exam results, which are further enhanced by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other efforts in the local environment.
With up to 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools seek to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can compile and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we find that modern languages remain a popular subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it hits the heart.”
It is an important reminder that we cannot only stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can look at the latest exam results this year, that language is the highest in the statistics with the most graduated exams in independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by SCIS’ 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students received the grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
It shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important competencies that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now perceived as subject selection at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools think and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that among the reasons employers could not occupy vacancies, 17% had to do with a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities will require language skills in the future, and these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career they choose, if they have learned a different language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage over the competitors.
According to a YouGov poll with over 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important to invest in language education for those who are children today.
When more languages are spoken, especially from developing countries, children have a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, there is a difference between schools in which languages are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classical modern languages, while others teach in languages that are expected to be most important to the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be a number of languages to choose from at independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed no matter what the future offers.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be truly important for the future of the country in a global business environment, and that needs to be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this award to Scotland’s youth.
We have to do it right.
