While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phase-divisioned" approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps. But his speech seemed important as it did not unambiguously reject unilateral disarmament, as has otherwise been the case in the past from Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim promised to work on “nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula” while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the Korean War, which took place in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown resistance to softening harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first’ and expands the pressure on sanctions to achieve their purpose by coercion and even opposes the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
"The notion that sanctions can put us on our knees is a dream of people who don't know who we are.
