Students at Harvard take courses on getting enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all undergraduate students more sleep. The purpose of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture, where studying all night held up by large amounts of caffeine.
A researcher has shown that students at the world’s best universities often don’t know the first thing to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, who is a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has made the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a speech about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"When the draft was finished, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why do I get to know this only now that I'm on the candidate?'
“She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits can improve one’s academic and sports performance as well as one’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the University’s health department, says the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that the students were in severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course consists, among other things, of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises, there is a picture of a college room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how your sporting performance is affected by lack of sleep, and how important good sleep habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how long-term lack of sleep increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on different icons on an interactive map of campus.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of the students right away.
But we think they have a right to know – just as we have a right to know how cigarettes affect health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride that is in taking an "allnighter" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have led to sleep deprivation being a growing problem.
The “secret weapon” against stress, fatigue and anxiety is good and adequate sleep, he said – it even counteracts weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to believe that one is hungry, why they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler organize the course last year when he took one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and made him work on making it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that the next step will be that all graduates will be offered a similar course before they continue their education.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm so that they know when to go to bed and when to get up. This can raise awareness of the harmful effects of light from electronic screens, which can crack at the rhythm of the day and make it harder to fall asleep.
