New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach Immune System to “See” Cancer Cells
New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach Immune System to “See” Cancer Cells and Kill them
Vaccine Teaches Immune System to Recognize Cancer Cells as Part of Treatment
The method consists of extracting immune cells from a patient and changing them in the laboratory.
They can then "see" the protein that is common to many cancers and where they are injected again
A test vaccine is promising in patients with a variety of cancers.
When a woman with ovarian cancer was treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells, the cancer disappeared for more than 18 months.
The method consists of extracting immune cells from patients and changing them in the laboratory so that they can "see" the protein called HER2, which many cancers have, and then inject the cells again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
